	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0313">313<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0313.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">

<h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">La Haie 6<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Mars 1783.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>En comenant par le plus press, voici une Lettre de Son Excellence le Ministre Plenipo: de cette rep. auprs de nos Et. Unis.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> Il ma charg en outre de vous demander les Eclaircissemens suivants.</p>
<p>1<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o.</span> Quels Meubles &amp; fournitures il lui convient principalement demporter avec lui dici, plutt que de les acheter &amp; faire faire  Philadelphie?</p>
<p>2<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o.</span> Sil devra faire une Entre publique, ou Sil pourra sen dispenser, sans se singulariser davec les autres Ministres Etrangers, &amp; sans compromettre la dignit de la Puissance qui lenvoie, dans lopinion de celle o il est envoy?</p>
<p>3<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o.</span> Dans le cas o lEntre publique Soit ncessaire, lequel lui tournera mieux  compte, ou de faire faire un carosse de parade (pour cette seule journe o il sen servira peut-tre) ici, ou  Philadelphie?</p>
<p>Mr. Wheelock est parti pour Amsterdam, content de moi. Mr. Van Berkel le Pensionaire,  qui je lai prsent, est davis quil ne propose laffaire ouvertement, que lorsque la conclusion gnrale de la paix aura remis les Esprits de ce pays dans une Assiete plus <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0314">[314<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0314.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>tranquille &amp; plus gaie. Jai accompagn les deux freres<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>  Leide o nous avons dn chez Mr. Luzac &amp; o Mr. Van der Kemp est entr de tout son coeur dans le Plan. Il doit avoir crit aujourdhui l-dessus au Professeur Oosterbaan  Amsterdam,<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> &amp;  deux autres maisons Anabatistes  Harlem &amp; en Frise. Il sera lui-mme  Amsterdam dune grande fte, qui Sy doera le 15  Mr. De Capelle du Pol &amp;  Mr. Van Berkel o laffaire pourra tre comence.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> E[nfin] Mr. Gyzelaar sinteressera aussi a la rus[site du] Plan, quand il sera temps de le proposer dans sa ville. Pour  La Haie, le meilleur nous a paru de ne point faire usage des Lettres pour Le P<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">ce.</span> &amp; pour M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">c</span>L,<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0005" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> au moins quant  prsent, &amp; jusqu-ce que la Russite ailleurs empche de tourner la proposition en ridicule, &amp; de la traverser.</p>
<p>Vous devez avoir reu actuellement, Messieurs, ainsi que les Ministres de France &amp; dEspagne, par ceux de la Rep<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span>  Paris, louverture dentamer la Ngociation pour un Trait de Garantie rciproque de la Libert des mers.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0006" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> Ces Messieurs comptent  cet gard, &amp; <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">principalement</span>, sur les promesses riteres que vous mavez autoris de leur faire, srs que vous ne vous laisserez point influer ni diriger par <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Shelburne &amp; Co</span>:, qui <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">sentendent</span>, disent-ils, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">come larrons en foire</span>. Vous naurez pas de peine  comprendre lallusion. Si cette convention pouvoit se faire avant la signature du Trait dfinitif, ce seroit le triomphe ici de nos rpublicains. Quelquun mayant object, que lAngl<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> pourroit en prendre ombrage Si ce Trait se faisoit avant lautre; <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Et depuis quand</span>, ai-je repliqu, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">la France a-t-elle recomenc  avoir peur de donner ombrage  lAngleterre?</span></p>
<p>Je Suis avec grand respect, &amp; en vous prsentant les obissances de ma famille avec les miennes, Monsieur / Votre trs-humble &amp; trs / obissant serviteur</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="translation">
<h2><span class="hi-all-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase;">Translation</span></h2>
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 6 March 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Beginning with the most urgent matter, here is a letter from his excellency the minister plenipotentiary of this republic to the United States.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> He has further instructed me to ask you the following questions:</p>
<p>1. What furnishings and supplies would it be advisable for him to take from here, rather than buying them or having them made in Philadelphia?</p>
<p>2. If he should make a public entrance or if he can dispense with this without appearing too different from the other foreign ministers or compromising the dignity of the power that is sending him, in the opinion of the power that receives him?</p>
<p>3. In case a public entrance is indeed necessary, which would turn best <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0315">[315<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0315.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>to his account, to have a ceremonial carriage made (for this one day when he might use it) here or in Philadelphia?</p>
<p>Mr. Wheelock has left for Amsterdam, quite pleased with me. Mr. Van Berckel the pensionary, to whom I introduced him, is of the opinion that he should only present the matter openly once the general conclusion of the peace treaty has restored peoples minds to a state of cheerfulness and calm. I accompanied both brothers<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> back to Leyden, where we had dinner at Mr. Luzacs house. Mr. Van der Kemp entered wholeheartedly into the plan. He was supposed to write about it today to Professor Oosterbaan in Amsterdam<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> and to two other Anabaptist houses in Haarlem and Friesland. He himself will be in Amsterdam on 15 March for a grand entertainment in honor of Mr. Van der Capellen tot den Pol and Mr. Van Berckel, at which the matter can be broached.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> Finally, Mr. Gyselaar too will take an interest in the plan when it is time to propose it in his town. As for The Hague, it seemed best to us not to use the letters for the prince and for MacLaine,<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0005" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> at least not now, until success obtained elsewhere prevents the proposal from being ridiculed and thwarted.</p>
<p>By now, gentlemen, you should have received from the ministers of the republic at Paris, at the same time as the ministers of France and Spain, an overture to open negotiations for a treaty of reciprocal guarantee of the freedom of the seas.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0006" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0208-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> These gentlemen are counting <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">heavily</span> on the oftrepeated promises you authorized me to give them, certain you will not allow yourself to be influenced or driven by <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Shelburne and Co.</span>, who <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">get on</span>, they say, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">like thieves at a fair</span>. You will easily understand this allusion. If this convention could take place before the definitive treaty is signed, it would be a triumph here for our republicans. Someone offered me the objection that England might take umbrage if this treaty is concluded before the other; <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">And</span>, said I, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">since when has France ever been afraid of giving umbrage to England?</span></p>
<p>I am with great respect, and in presenting my familys compliments with my own, sir, your very humble and very obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
